src/sda.cpp (sda)  (ported from Lucas Franca's own legacy `mrug` tool --
same author, no licensing conflict; DEVIATES from the original code, see
below)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
Algorithm: windowed Root-Mean-Square deviation from the local mean
("Standard Deviation Analysis" / SDA), no detrending, fit via power-law
regression across window sizes -- Russ JC. Fractal Surfaces. New York,
NY: Plenum; 1994.

This is the method described in the Materials and Methods of:
  da Silva Costa I, Gamundi A, Miranda JGV, Franca LGS, De Santana CN,
  Montoya P. Altered functional performance in patients with
  fibromyalgia. Front Hum Neurosci 2017;11:14.
(L. Franca is a co-author; the paper computed body-sway Hurst exponents
with this method.)

Ported from `mrug.cpp`/`mrug.h` (the `calcM()`/`localM()` code path; the
sibling `calc()`/`local()` path implements a different, linear-detrended,
mean-absolute-deviation measure and was NOT ported -- it is not the
method described in the 2017 paper).

Unlike every other entry in this file, this is not a faithful port: the
exact snapshot of `mrug` used to generate the 2017 paper's results could
not be identified, so bit-exact parity was not a reachable (or
meaningful) goal. Three issues were found in the available copy of the
legacy code and fixed rather than reproduced:

  1. The class had a member variable `int k` that was shadowed by a
     same-named local variable inside `calc()`/`calcM()`. The very first
     call to the per-window roughness function at each scale used
     `this->k` (the uninitialized member) instead of the local `k`,
     making the first window's size undefined at every scale. All
     subsequent windows at that scale used the correct local `k`. Fixed
     by using a single, correctly-scoped scale value throughout.
  2. `read()` used a `do { ... } while (!file.eof())` loop, a classic
     C++ anti-pattern: `eof()` is only set *after* a failed read
     attempt, so the loop always executes one extra iteration, which
     (via a post-increment inside the same statement) inflates the
     point count by one and leaves the last row duplicating the
     previous one. Not directly applicable to this R port (R/base
     handles reading the input vector), but noted here since it means
     any comparison against the original tool's own file-based output
     would already be off by this bug before `calc`/`calcM` even run.
  3. `calc()`/`calcM()` always begin their windowing from index 1, not
     index 0, silently excluding the series' first sample from every
     window regardless of series length (`main.cpp`'s CLI tool always
     passed a starting index of 1). This looks like an oversight rather
     than an intentional offset. Fixed to start from index 0, so the
     first sample is included like every other.

Because of (1)-(3), `sda()`'s output should be treated as a corrected
re-implementation of the published SDA/Hurst method, not a bit-exact
reproduction of the specific numbers in the 2017 paper -- those were
almost certainly generated by a version of `mrug` affected by at least
bug (1) and possibly (2)-(3), which could not be recovered for
comparison.

The scale-stepping scheme (geometric growth by a factor of 1.1, with
forced +1 increments below window size 20 to avoid duplicate integer
window sizes at small scales) is preserved from the original, since it's
a deliberate sampling design rather than a bug. This is implemented in
R/fractal.R (.sda_scales()); src/sda.cpp only computes the fluctuation
function for a given set of window sizes.
