src/entropy.cpp (perm_entropy) and src/fractal_nonlinear.cpp
(petrosian_fd, hjorth_parameters, num_zerocross)  (ported from Lucas
Franca's own mrpheus package — same author, no licensing conflict)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
These four functions were originally implemented in mrpheus's
src/staging_features.cpp as part of its AASM sleep-staging feature
pipeline (a faithful R/C++ port of the YASA/antropy Python feature set;
see mrpheus's own NEWS.md and staging_features.R header for that
parity-validation history). Centralised here so mrpheus (and other
ecosystem packages) can eventually depend on Rtractor for these general-
purpose complexity measures rather than maintaining private duplicates,
per the ecosystem's "wrap, don't reimplement" and isolation principles.

Re-validated directly against the antropy Python library (v0.2.2) on
synthetic and fixed-vector test data during this port:
  - perm_entropy: exact match on the normalized value (default,
    normalize=TRUE). The *unnormalized* raw value is not directly
    comparable between the two: antropy computes raw entropy in log
    base 2 (bits), this port in natural log (nats). The normalized
    ratio is base-independent, which is why it matches exactly while
    the raw values differ by a factor of ln(2).
  - petrosian_fd: exact match
  - num_zerocross: exact match
  - hjorth_parameters: agrees closely but NOT exactly, by design. This
    port uses Bessel-corrected (ddof=1) variance throughout, matching
    mrpheus's original implementation (itself deliberately matching R's
    var() convention, per mrpheus's own source comments) rather than
    antropy's population-variance (ddof=0) convention. The discrepancy
    shrinks as length(x) grows (negligible for epoch-length signals,
    ~1000+ samples) but is clearly visible for short series (e.g. ~0.1%
    difference at length 20) -- it is a genuine convention difference,
    not floating-point noise.

Note: Rtractor's higuchi_fd() (see the Higuchi entry above) was
independently ported from a different MATLAB reference, and was found
to agree exactly with mrpheus/antropy's higuchi_fd for realistic epoch
lengths (kmax << length(x)); the two only diverge in the edge case where
kmax approaches length(x), so no reconciliation was needed.

References:
  Bandt C, Pompe B. Permutation entropy: a natural complexity measure
  for time series. Phys Rev Lett 2002;88:174102.

  Petrosian A. Kolmogorov complexity of finite sequences and recognition
  of different preictal EEG patterns. Proceedings of the Eighth IEEE
  Symposium on Computer-Based Medical Systems 1995:212-217.

  Hjorth B. EEG analysis based on time domain properties.
  Electroencephalogr Clin Neurophysiol 1970;29(3):306-310.

  Vallat R, Walker MP. An open-source, high-performance tool for
  automated sleep staging. eLife 2021;10:e70092.
